Unit Testing Form Fields

03
On this page
  1. 🛠 Challenge: Write Tests for Radio Button Reachability
  2. 🛠 Solution: Write a Test for Radio Button Reachability
    1. Test 1: Acts as One Tab Stop
    2. Test 2: Enables a Custom Field Amount

CampSpots has a Passes page where the user can choose a plan and make a payment to register for the site.

The form features donation options for the user to choose a radio button or specify an amount in an input box.

This functionality is part of the PresetsCustomAmounts subcomponent of the Payment Form. Its source can be found at components/payment-form/presets-custom-amounts.js.

Originally in the PresetsCustomAmounts component, someone using tab would skip past the radio buttons and over to the “Other amount” field with no way to move back.

This was fixed by conditionally setting the tabindex of the component based on which radio option was checked.

// excerpt from presets-custom-amounts.js
<input
	id="amt_custom_text"
	onFocus={focusInCustomInput}
	placeholder="$ Other amount"
	tabIndex={customAmtRadio.current && customAmtRadio.current.checked ? '0' : '-1'}
	type="text"
/>
// excerpt from presets-custom-amounts.js
<input
	id="amt_custom_text"
	onFocus={focusInCustomInput}
	placeholder="$ Other amount"
	tabIndex={customAmtRadio.current && customAmtRadio.current.checked ? '0' : '-1'}
	type="text"
/>

Now would be a good time for you to write some tests to ensure this component doesn’t stop working.

🛠 Challenge: Write Tests for Radio Button Reachability

Inside of components/payment-form/__tests__/presets-custom-amounts.test.js you will find a starting point for two tests related to the PresetsCustomAmounts component.

Both tests render the form along with a plain button.

describe('Preset amount radio buttons', () => {
    it('acts as one tab stop',  async () => {
        render(
            <form>
                <PresetsCustomAmounts amounts={[10, 25, 50]} />
                <button>Text</button>
            </form>
        )

        // your test code here
    })

    it('enables a custom field amount', () => {
        render(
            <form>
                <PresetsCustomAmounts amounts={[10, 25, 50]} />
                <button>Text</button>
            </form>
        )
        
        // your test code here
    })
 })

For the first test, you need to ensure that the form acts as a single tab stop.

If you were using your keyboard to interact with the form, the first time you hit tab the focus would be on the first radio button. Then the second time you hit tab, the focus would be on the button.

The second test builds on to the behavior from the first.

If the user tabs into the radio selection buttons and then clicks the “Custom” option, hitting tab should put focus into the text box.

Reference the PresetsCustomAmounts component source code, as well as tests and resources in the previous section.

And remember, there’s a completed solution in the exercise1-jest directory if you get really stuck!

🛠 Solution: Write a Test for Radio Button Reachability

These are my solutions, but keep in mind there are multiple ways to fill in these tests to make them pass.

Test 1: Acts as One Tab Stop

In this test, we need references to the first radio option as well as the button element that comes after it.

To get the radio button, I’ll use the getByDisplayValue query to look for the value of 10. This was the first value of the amounts array we passed into the component.

For the button, I’ll use getByRole as we’ve done previously.

After simulating one tab press, I’ll expect that the first radio button has focus. Simulating a second tab press, I’ll expect that the button has focus.

Here’s what the test code looks like all together:

it('acts as one tab stop',  async () => {
         render(
             <form>
                 <PresetsCustomAmounts amounts={[10, 25, 50]} />
                 <button>Text</button>
             </form>
         )
  
         const firstRadio = screen.getByDisplayValue(10)
         const button = screen.getByRole('button')
         
         await user.tab()
         expect(firstRadio).toHaveFocus()
 
         await user.tab()
 
         expect(button).toHaveFocus()
     })
it('acts as one tab stop',  async () => {
         render(
             <form>
                 <PresetsCustomAmounts amounts={[10, 25, 50]} />
                 <button>Text</button>
             </form>
         )
  
         const firstRadio = screen.getByDisplayValue(10)
         const button = screen.getByRole('button')
         
         await user.tab()
         expect(firstRadio).toHaveFocus()
 
         await user.tab()
 
         expect(button).toHaveFocus()
     })

Test 2: Enables a Custom Field Amount

For this test, in addition to the first radio button we also need to find the custom radio button and input.

Referencing the source code for the PresetsCustomAmounts component, we can see that the value of the custom radio button is “Custom” and the placeholder for the input is “$ Other amount”. I’ll write queries for these using the getByDisplayValue and getByPlaceholderText queries.

Tabbing to the first radio button and expecting it to have focus will be the same as in the first test.

However this time, I’ll fire a .click() event on the custom radio option. This should mean that it is now checked.

From there, I’ll simulate a press of the tab key and expect that the text input is now focused.

Here’s what this code looks like all together:

it('enables a custom field amount', async () => {
         render(
             <form>
                 <PresetsCustomAmounts amounts={[10, 25, 50]} />
                 <button>Text</button>
             </form>
         )
             
         const firstRadio = screen.getByDisplayValue(10)
         const customRadio = screen.getByDisplayValue('Custom')
         const customInputText = screen.getByPlaceholderText('$ Other amount')
         
         await user.tab()
         expect(firstRadio).toHaveFocus()
 
         // applying pointer event as arrow keys aren't yet
         // implemented on radios in user-event
         customRadio.click()
         expect(customRadio).toBeChecked()
 
         await user.tab()
 
         expect(customInputText).toHaveFocus()
     })
it('enables a custom field amount', async () => {
